## Premiere Pro UXP Plugin manifest.json (Version 5)

Each UXP plugin must have one manifest.json file that the host application uses to load and manage the plugin. In addition to core metadata such as the plugin's name, version, icons, and entry points, the manifest specifies permissions, compatibility details, and other definitions that shape how the plugin integrates with the host environment.(no content)The `manifestVersion` field indicates the version of the manifest schema. Premiere supports version "5".(no content)The entrypoints array defines the entrypoints that the plugin provides; currently, only Commands and Panels are supported.

### Example Code Structure

Here's an example manifest.json structure based on the documentation:

```json
{
  "manifestVersion": 5,
  "id": "YOUR_PLUGIN_ID_HERE",
  "name": "My Premiere Pro Plugin",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "main": "index.html",
  "host": {
    "app": "premierepro",
    "minVersion": "25.0.0"
  },
  "entrypoints": [
    {
      "type": "command",
      "id": "myCommand",
      "label": {
        "default": "My Command"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "panel",
      "id": "myPanel",
      "label": {
        "default": "My Panel"
      },
      "minimumSize": {"width": 230, "height": 200},
      "maximumSize": {"width": 2000, "height": 2000},
      "preferredDockedSize": {"width": 230, "height": 300},
      "preferredFloatingSize": {"width": 230, "height": 300}
    }
  ],
  "icons": [
    {
      "width": 23,
      "height": 23,
      "path": "icons/icon_dark.png",
      "scale": [1, 2],
      "theme": ["dark", "darkest"]
    },
    {
      "width": 23,
      "height": 23,
      "path": "icons/icon_light.png",
      "scale": [1, 2],
      "theme": ["lightest", "light"]
    }
  ]
}
```

### Key Features of Manifest v5

Starting with v5, any permissions not explicitly declared in the manifest are not granted by default. In order for your plugin to use the network, you must define domains that your plugin will access. You can do this by adding the network object to the requiredPermissions section of the manifest.

### Command Entrypoints

Command entrypoints are the most common type of entrypoint. They allow you to add commands to the Premiere Pro user interface. When the user runs a command, your plugin can perform a variety of actions, such as opening a dialog and changing the document.(no content)In your manifest.json file, register a new command-type entrypoint. This will add a new command entrypoint with the ID "myCommand" to your plugin. It will show up as My Command in the Premiere Pro user interface.

### Additional Resources

When building UXP plugins for Premiere, you don't need to start from scratch. Adobe provides two types of resources: Samples (complete, working examples that demonstrate specific features or use cases) and Starters (minimal templates with framework setup to help you begin a new plugin project).


